<h1>@HI{{koto}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong>
<li> @Ai{{}} <strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong>
<li> @Ana{{}} <strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong> is a nominaliser that indicates the speaker's relative lack of empathy with the
content of the nominalised sentence.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong> turns a whole sentence into a noun phrase which can then be used anywhere that a noun
phrase can normally be used.
</p>

<p>
Unlike the nominaliser <a href="grammar-no-nominaliser.html">@HI{{no}}</a>, <strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong> tends to indicate
something to which the speaker does not feel very close.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{suisu}}ga kireina<strong>koto</strong>ha @KJ{{copy^true}}de @KJ{{know}}tteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      From photographs I know that Switzerland is beautiful.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
There are various structures where <strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong> is used and @HI{{no}} is not:
<ul>
<li> ... @HI{{ha <strong>koto</strong> desu.}}
<li> ... @HI{{<strong>koto</strong> ga aru}} ...
<li> ... @HI{{<strong>koto</strong> ga dekiru}} ...
<li> ... @HI{{<strong>koto</strong> ni naru}} ...
<li> ... @HI{{<strong>koto</strong> ni suru}} ...
<li> ... @HI{{<strong>koto</strong> ha}} ...
</ul>
</p>

